<DocsLayout title="Introduction — Band Docs">
  <h1>Introduction</h1>

  <p>
    You started using an AI coding agent on one project. Then a second agent. Now
    you've got Claude Code running in a Cursor terminal, Codex in a VS Code
    window, OpenCode in a Zed split, three half-finished branches, and no idea
    which one was actually working on the bug. Your IDE wasn't designed for
    this &mdash; you're using it to babysit code an agent wrote, not to write code
    yourself.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Band is the agent-first IDE.</strong> It's a desktop app built from
    the ground up around AI coding agents: chat panes for talking to them, a
    code editor and file tree to review what they've done, terminals and
    browsers to verify it works, and git worktree workspaces to keep parallel
    agents from stepping on each other &mdash; all in one window.
  </p>

